	<h1>The American Opportunity Tax Credit</h1>

	<p>Keep in mind that a tax credit is not financial aid.  No check gets cut from anyone to the student, parents, or school.  A tax credit is a direct reduction of the amount of tax money you owe the IRS.  A tax credit is different than a tax deduction.  With deductions, the amount of income the IRS may tax is reduced.  </p>

	<h3>Who Qualifies for this Tax Credit?</h3>

	<p>Because a tax credit is a direct reduction of the amount you owe the IRS, one needs to owe taxes to qualify for a tax credit such as the Hope Scholarship Tax Credit.  If you owe no taxes, then you have no eligibility for this tax credit.  If you owe less in taxes than the total amount of the credit, the credit will reduce your liability to the IRS to zero dollars.  </p>
	<p>The Hope Scholarship Tax Credit is only good for the first 2 years of a student's post-secondary education.</p>
	<p>This benefit is available to parents and any or all dependents.  To qualify, the student must:</p>

	<ul>

		<li>Be in a degree seeking program (taking miscellaneous classes at a local college does not qualify)
		<li>Be at least a half-time student for at least one semester
		<li>Have no drug convictions by the end of the year
		<li>Be within his/her first 2 years of post-secondary education

	</ul>

